#1 Resected, metastatic rectosigmoid adenocarcinoma to the liver, KRAS-mutant
I have reviewed all of the above in-depth with Mr. Keen as well as his significant otherwise and Dr. Botello.  At this point, fortunately, Mr. Keen has had a complete surgical resection of his primary mass in his rectum as well as his liver metastasis.  There does not appear on imaging or blood work to be any evidence of recurrent or metastatic disease at this point.  Mr. Keen understands he is at high-risk for recurrence, and therefore we are recommending an additional course of chemotherapy.  As he has had such a good response to FOLFOX with overall good tolerance, we have recommended an additional four to six cycles with dose adjustments as cycles continue, based on tolerance to oxaliplatin.  He plans on getting this treatment at-home locally in Sutherlin, which is acceptable.
We would recommend that Mr. Keen return after he completes his chemotherapy and has an interval month off for consideration by Dr. Zamora for reversal of his ileostomy.  He knows to call at any time if there are problems or concerns.
#2 Port-A-Cath-associated right arm DVT
Mr. Keen has had a Port-A-Cath-associated DVT and subsequently had that Port-A-Cath removed.  He is scheduled to see our surgeons tomorrow for consideration of a new Port-A-Cath, which he will need for chemotherapy.  From my perspective, he would be medically acceptable for this planned procedure.  He is on blood thinners due to his prior Port-A-Cath-associated blood clot, and I have asked him to take half the dose of his Fragmin the night before, omit Fragmin in the morning of his procedure, and then he can restart his Fragmin that evening.  He will eventually transition to Coumadin, but he will do this locally with his home medical provider.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

[end section id="20112"]

